Ordered Clustering-Based Semantic Music Recommender System Using Deep Learning Selection
Description
This repository contains the implementation of an ordered clustering-based semantic music recommender system that integrates semantic analysis of user-generated textual comments with supervised learning models. The proposed framework is designed to address core challenges in music recommendation, including user preference modeling, similarity estimation, rating prediction, and the cold-start problem.
The published study presents a novel music recommendation system designed to improve personalization on streaming platforms, particularly addressing the challenges of the cold start problem. The proposed approach combines order-based clustering with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to leverage both semantic and behavioral information from users. Initially, the system calculates semantic similarity between users by analyzing their textual comments and sequentially clusters them into groups of decreasing similarity. Within each cluster, users’ favorite music and ratings are examined to identify shared preferences, which are then used as training input for a CNN to predict ratings for unreviewed music. Additionally, the method incorporates users’ listening behavior and music popularity to enhance recommendations, particularly for new users. By integrating semantic similarity, rating patterns, and music popularity, the system effectively predicts user preferences and generates highly accurate recommendations. Experimental results demonstrate superior performance compared to traditional classifiers, achieving low mean absolute error (MAE ≈ 0.0017), low root mean square error (RMSE ≈ 0.0017), a hit rate of 82.45%, average nDCG of 82.3%, and new rating prediction accuracy of 99.388%, confirming the effectiveness of combining semantic analysis and deep learning in music recommendation.
DOI: 10.32604/cmc.2025.061343
