Computing Infrastructure
Experiments and simulations were conducted under the following environment:
•	Hardware: Laptop ASUS N56J – Intel Core i7, 8 GB RAM
•	Operating System: Windows 10 (64-bit)
•	Software Environment: MATLAB R2021b

Dataset Information
The system operates on the dataset stored in:
music_album_reviews.csv
The dataset includes:
•	reviewerID – Unique user identifiers
•	asin1 – Music (item) identifiers
•	reviewText – User textual comments/reviews
•	overall – Numerical ratings assigned by users
The data represent user interactions with music items, combining both explicit feedback (ratings) and implicit semantic information (textual comments).

Code Overview
The implementation performs the following major operations:
1.	Data Preprocessing
o	Random sampling and permutation of observations
o	Missing value handling via constant imputation
o	Extraction of unique users and items
2.	Semantic Representation
o	Tokenization of textual comments
o	Stop-word removal
o	Bag-of-words construction
o	Vocabulary-based document representation
3.	Similarity Computation
o	Cosine similarity between semantic vectors
o	Construction of a semantic similarity matrix
4.	Sequential (Ordered) Clustering
o	Users grouped based on similarity intensity
o	Clusters arranged from highest to lowest semantic proximity
5.	Ranking-Based Similarity
o	Identification of common preferred music
o	Similarity estimation using shared rankings
6.	Rating Estimation
o	CNN-based prediction of music ratings
o	Comparative evaluation using KNN, Decision Tree, Naïve Bayes, and SVM
7.	Cold-Start Strategy
o	Recommendation based on music popularity scores
8.	Evaluation and Visualization
o	Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F-measure
o	MAE and RMSE analysis
o	Confusion matrices and performance plots

Methodology
The recommender system follows a multi-stage modeling strategy:
1. Semantic Similarity Modeling
User profiles are represented through semantic features extracted from textual comments. Cosine similarity is used to quantify semantic proximity between users.
2. Ordered Clustering
Sequential clustering organizes users into ordered clusters reflecting decreasing similarity levels. The first cluster contains users with the strongest semantic alignment.
3. Ranking Similarity Analysis
Within clusters, user preferences are compared based on shared favorite music. Ranking similarity captures agreement in rating behavior.
4. Deep Learning-Based Rating Prediction
Semantic features and rating information serve as training inputs to convolutional neural networks, enabling prediction of ratings for unseen items.
5. Popularity-Aware Recommendation
Music popularity is derived from aggregate rating statistics and incorporated to mitigate cold-start limitations.

Assessment Metrics
Performance evaluation relies on standard classification and prediction metrics:
•	Accuracy – Measures overall correctness of predictions
•	Recall – Evaluates the ability to identify relevant items
•	Precision – Assesses correctness of positive predictions
•	F-measure – Harmonic mean of Precision and Recall
Error-based metrics:
•	MAE (Mean Absolute Error) – Quantifies average prediction deviation
•	RMSE (Root Mean Square Error) – Emphasizes larger prediction errors
These metrics provide complementary perspectives on predictive reliability and recommendation quality.

Requirements
The following MATLAB libraries are typically required to reproduce the workflow:
•	Text Analytics Toolbox – for text preprocessing, tokenization, bag-of-words modeling, and cosine similarity computation.
•	Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox – for KNN, Decision Tree, SVM, Naive Bayes classifiers, and sampling utilities.
•	Deep Learning Toolbox – for constructing and training the convolutional neural network (CNN) used for rating prediction.
•	MATLAB Base Functions – for data handling, plotting, and matrix operations.
These toolboxes ensure full execution of preprocessing, clustering, similarity computation, classification, deep learning, and visualization steps in the provided scripts.
Usage Instructions
1.	Place the dataset file “music_album_reviews.mat” in the working directory.
2.	Ensure all required Python libraries are installed.
3.	Execute the main script after adapting MATLAB-specific logic (if converting) or run within a compatible environment.
4.	Review generated plots and metrics for performance interpretation.

Conclusions
The proposed framework demonstrates that integrating semantic analysis with ordered clustering and deep learning can effectively model user preferences and predict music ratings. Semantic similarity derived from textual comments provides valuable information beyond numerical ratings alone.
The hybrid strategy improves recommendation robustness while offering a practical solution to cold-start scenarios via popularity-aware mechanisms.

Limitations
Several limitations should be acknowledged:
•	Dependence on the quality and representativeness of textual comments
•	Sensitivity of cosine similarity to vocabulary construction
•	Potential bias introduced by missing value imputation
•	Model performance variability across datasets
•	Popularity-based cold-start mitigation may reduce personalization
Future research may explore advanced embeddings, contextual models, and dynamic preference learning.

